<li>Simakawa, Viviane Vergueiro, 2018, <em>Sou travestis: estuando a
cisgeneridade como uma possibilidade decolonial</em>, Brasilia:
Pad&ecirc; Editorial.</li>

<li>Smilges, J. Logan, 2022, &ldquo;Neurotrans&rdquo;, <em>TSQ:
Transgender Studies Quarterly</em>, 9(4): 634&ndash;652.
doi:10.1215/23289252-10133831</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, &ldquo;Seasons of Nonbinary and
Neurodivergence; or, So What If We&rsquo;re All X?&rdquo;, <em>WSQ:
Women&rsquo;s Studies Quarterly</em>, 51(3&ndash;4): 29&ndash;43.
doi:10.1353/wsq.2023.a910065</li>

<li>Smith-Johnson, Madeline, 2022, &ldquo;Transgender Adults Have
Higher Rates Of Disability Than Their Cisgender Counterparts: Study
Examines Rates of Disability among Transgender Adults and Cisgender
Adults&rdquo;, <em>Health Affairs</em>, 41(10): 1470&ndash;1476.
doi:10.1377/hlthaff.2022.00500</li>

<li>Snorton, C. Riley, 2017, <em>Black on Both Sides: A Racial History
of Trans Identity</em>, Minneapolis, MN: University of Minnesota
Press.</li>

<li>Snorton, C. Riley and Jin Haritaworn, 2013, &ldquo;Trans
Necropolitics: A Transnational Reflection on Violence, Death, and the
Trans of Color Afterlife&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#TSR2013">Stryker and Aizura 2013</a>:
 pp. 66&ndash;76.</li>

<li>Spade, Dean, 2011 [2015], <em>Normal Life: Administrative
Violence, Critical Trans Politics, and the Limits of Law</em>,
Brooklyn, NY: South End Press. Revised and expanded edition, 2015,
Durham, NC: Duke University Press. doi:10.1215/9780822374794</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Mutilating Gender&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#TSR2013">Stryker and Aizura 2013</a>:
 331&ndash;348.</li>

<li>Spillers, Hortense J., 2003, <em>Black, White, and in Color:
Essays on American Literature and Culture</em>, Chicago: University of
Chicago Press.</li>

<li>Spivak, Gayatri Chakravorty, 1999, <em>A Critique of Postcolonial
Reason: Toward a History of the Vanishing Present</em>, Cambridge, MA:
Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>Stanley, Eric A., 2017, &ldquo;Anti-Trans Optics: Recognition,
Opacity, and the Image of Force&rdquo;, <em>South Atlantic
Quarterly</em>, 116(3): 612&ndash;620.
doi:10.1215/00382876-3961732</li>

<li>Steinbock, Eliza, Marianna Szczygielska, and Anthony Wagner, 2017,
&ldquo;Thinking Linking&rdquo;, <em>Angelaki</em>, 22(2): 1&ndash;10.
doi:10.1080/0969725X.2017.1322801</li>

<li>Stephano, Oli, 2019, &ldquo;Irreducibility and (Trans) Sexual
Difference&rdquo;, <em>Hypatia</em>, 34(1): 141&ndash;154.
doi:10.1111/hypa.12447</li>

<li>Stewart, Amy Ray, 2017, &ldquo;Transgender Subjectivity in Revolt:
Kristevan Psychoanalysis and the Intimate Politics of Rebirth&rdquo;,
<em>TSQ: Transgender Studies Quarterly</em>, 4(3&ndash;4):
577&ndash;607. doi:10.1215/23289252-4189974</li>

<li>Stone, Sandy. 1987 [2006], &ldquo;The Empire Strikes Back: A
Posttranssexual Manifesto&rdquo;, written in 1987. Reprinted in
 <a href="#TSR2006">Stryker and Whittle 2006</a>:
 221&ndash;235.</li>

<li>Stryker, Susan, 1994, &ldquo;My Words to Victor Frankenstein Above
the Village of Chamounix&rdquo;, <em>GLQ: A Journal of Lesbian and Gay
Studies</em> 1(3): 237&ndash;254.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2006, &ldquo;(De)Subjugated Knowledges: An
Introduction to Trans Studies&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#TSR2006">Stryker and Whittle 2006</a>:
 1&ndash;17.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008a, &ldquo;Dungeon Intimacies: The
Poetics of Transsexual Sadomasochism&rdquo;, <em>Parallax</em>, 14(1):
36&ndash;47. doi:10.1080/13534640701781362</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008b [2017], <em>Transgender History</em>
(Seal Studies), Berkeley, CA: Seal Press. Second edition as
<em>Transgender History: The Roots of Today&rsquo;s Revolution</em>,
New York, NY: Seal Press, Hachette Book Group, 2017.</li>

<li id="TSR2013">Stryker, Susan and Aren Z. Aizura (eds.), 2013,
<em>The Transgender Studies Reader 2</em>, New York: Routledge.</li>

<li>Stryker, Susan and Talia Mae Bettcher (eds.), 2016,
<em>Trans/Feminism</em>, special issue of <em>TSQ: Transgender Studies
Quarterly</em>, 3(1&ndash;2).</li>

<li>Stryker, Susan, Paisley Currah, and Lisa Jean Moore, 2008a,
&ldquo;Introduction: Trans-, Trans, or Transgender?&rdquo;, <em>WSQ:
Women&rsquo;s Studies Quarterly</em>, 36(3&ndash;4): 11&ndash;22.
doi:10.1353/wsq.0.0112</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash; (eds.), 2008b, <em>Trans-</em>, special
issue of <em>WSQ: Women&rsquo;s Studies Quarterly</em>,
36(3&ndash;4).</li>

<li id="TSR2006">Stryker, Susan and Stephen Whittle (eds.), 2006,
<em>The Transgender Studies Reader</em>, New York: Routledge.
doi:10.4324/9780203955055</li>

<li><em>TIME Magazine</em>, 2014, Cover title: &ldquo;The Transgender
Tipping Point: America&rsquo;s next civil rights frontier&rdquo;, 9
June 183(22).</li>

<li>Thornton, Max, 2019, &ldquo;Trans/Criptions: Gender, Disability,
and Liturgical Experience&rdquo;, <em>TSQ: Transgender Studies
Quarterly</em>, 6(3): 358&ndash;367. doi:10.1215/23289252-7549456</li>

<li>Tudor, Alyosxa, 2021, &ldquo;Decolonizing Trans/Gender Studies?
Teaching Gender, Race, and Sexuality in Times of the Rise of the
Global Right&rdquo;, <em>TSQ: Transgender Studies Quarterly</em>,
8(2): 238&ndash;256. doi:10.1215/23289252-8890523</li>

<li>Vakoch, Douglas A. (ed.), 2020, <em>Transecology: Transgender
Perspectives on Environment and Nature</em> (Routledge Studies in
Gender and Environments), Abingdon/New York: Routledge.
doi:10.4324/9780429023811</li>

<li>Viloria, Hida and Maria Nieto, 2020, <em>The Spectrum of Sex: The
Science of Male, Female, and Intersex</em>, London/Philadelphia:
Jessica Kingsley Publishers.</li>

<li>Washburn, Red and JV Fuqua, 2023, &ldquo;Introduction to Special
Issue, Nonbinary&rdquo;, <em>WSQ: Women&rsquo;s Studies
Quarterly</em>, 51(3&ndash;4): 14&ndash;23.
doi:10.1353/wsq.2023.a910063</li>

<li>Wark, McKenzie, 2020, <em>Reverse Cowgirl</em>, South Padadena,
CA: Semiotext(e).</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, <em>Raving</em> (Practices), Durham,
NC: Duke University Press. doi:10.1215/9781478024040</li>

<li>Wayar, Marlene, 2019, <em>Travesti: una teor&iacute;a lo
suficientemente buena</em>, Buenos Aires: Editorial Muchas
Nueces.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2024, &ldquo;Latin American Travesti/Trans
Theory&rdquo;, trans. Roc&iacute;o Pichon-Rivi&egrave;re, in
 <a href="#">Zurn, Pitts, Bettcher, and DiPietro 2024</a>,
 pp. 254&ndash;277.</li>

<li>Weil, Abraham, 2022, &ldquo;Transmolecular Revolution&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#cremin2022">Cremin 2022</a>:
 129&ndash;150.</li>

<li>Wilkerson, Abby L., 2012, &ldquo;Normate Sex and Its
Discontents&rdquo;, in <em>Sex and Disability</em>, Robert McRuer and
Anna Mollow (eds.), Durham, NC: Duke University Press, 183&ndash;207.
doi:10.1215/9780822394877-010</li>

<li>Witt, Charlotte, 2011, <em>The Metaphysics of Gender</em> (Studies
in Feminist Philosophy), Oxford/New York: Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199740413.001.0001</li>

<li>Wolff, Michelle, David A. Rubin, and Amanda Lock Swarr (eds.),
2022, <em>The Intersex Issue</em>, special issue of <em>TSQ:
Transgender Studies Quarterly</em>, 9(2).</li>

<li>Zurn, Perry, 2019, &ldquo;Waste Culture and Isolation: Prisons,
Toilets, and Gender Segregation&rdquo;, <em>Hypatia</em>, 34(4):
668&ndash;689. doi:10.1111/hypa.12498</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021a, &ldquo;Trans Curiosity: Beyond the
Curio&rdquo;, in his <em>Curiosity and Power: The Politics of
Inquiry</em>, Minneapolis, MN: University of Minnesota Press,
173&ndash;198.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021b, &ldquo;Feminist Curiosity&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 16(9): e12761.
doi:10.1111/phc3.12761</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, &ldquo;The Path of Friction: On
Hale&rsquo;s &lsquo;Rules&rsquo; for Accountability to and within
Trans Communities&rdquo;, <em>TSQ: Transgender Studies Quarterly</em>,
10(1): 71&ndash;85. doi:10.1215/23289252-10273252</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, forthcoming-a, <em>How We Make Each Other:
Trans Life at the Edge of the University</em>, Durham, NC: Duke
University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, forthcoming-b, &ldquo;Trans Philosophy: A
Tale of Two Futures,&rdquo; <em>APA Studies on Feminism and
Philosophy</em> 24(1).</li>

<li>Zurn, Perry and Andrea J. Pitts, 2020, &ldquo;Trans Philosophy:
The Early Years&rdquo;, <em>APA Newsletter on LGBTQ Issues in
Philosophy</em>, 20(1): 1&ndash;11.
 [<a href="https://cdn.ymaws.com/www.apaonline.org/resource/collection/B4B9E534-A677-4F29-8DC9-D75A5F16CC55/LGBTQV20n1.pdf" target="other">Zurn and Pitts 2020 available online (pdf)</a>]</li>
 
<li id="ZPBD2024">Zurn, Perry, Andrea J. Pitts, Talia Mae Bettcher,
and PJ DiPietro (eds.), 2024, <em>Trans Philosophy</em>, Minneapolis,
MN: University of Minnesota Press.</li>
</ul>
